            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this alimony calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                There is no single universal formula for alimony (spousal
                support). Courts usually look at many factors, and some
                jurisdictions have detailed statutory guidelines while others
                give judges broad discretion. This calculator uses a
                transparent, generic method to give you a
                <strong>ballpark estimate</strong> of:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  an indicative <strong>monthly alimony payment</strong>, and
                </li>
                <li>
                  a suggested <strong>duration of payments</strong> based on
                  marriage length.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                It is inspired by common guideline-style approaches used in
                several U.S. states and other countries, but it is
                <strong>not tied to any specific law</strong>. Always treat the
                result as an educational starting point, not a prediction of
                what a court will order.
              </p>

              <h3>Step 1 – Income gap between spouses</h3>
              <p>
                First, the calculator finds the difference between the payer’s
                and recipient’s gross annual income:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code
                  >Income gap = max( Payer income − Recipient income, 0 )</code
                >
              </div>
              <p>
                If the lower-earning spouse actually earns more, the gap is set
                to zero and the calculator suggests no alimony.
              </p>

              <h3>Step 2 – Base alimony rate</h3>
              <p>
                Many guideline systems use a percentage of the income gap. This
                tool uses a conservative sliding scale:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Short marriages (&lt; 5 years):</strong> 15% of the
                  income gap
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Medium marriages (5–15 years):</strong> 20% of the
                  income gap
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Long marriages (&gt; 15 years):</strong> 25% of the
                  income gap
                </li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>Base annual alimony = Income gap × Base rate</code>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 3 – Adjustment for dependent children</h3>
              <p>
                Child support is legally separate from alimony, but in practice,
                caring for children can increase the recipient’s need. This
                calculator adds a small adjustment:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  +2 percentage points to the base rate for each dependent
                  child,
                </li>
                <li>capped at an extra 10 percentage points total.</li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>
                  Adjusted rate = Base rate + min( Number of children × 0.02,
                  0.10 )<br />
                  Adjusted annual alimony = Income gap × Adjusted rate
                </code>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 4 – Reasonableness cap</h3>
              <p>
                To avoid unrealistic results, the calculator caps alimony so
                that the payer keeps at least
                <strong>55% of their gross income</strong>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>
                  Max annual alimony = Payer income × 45%<br />
                  Final annual alimony = min( Adjusted annual alimony, Max
                  annual alimony )
                </code>
              </div>
              <p>The monthly payment is simply:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>Monthly alimony = Final annual alimony ÷ 12</code>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 5 – Suggested duration</h3>
              <p>
                Duration rules differ widely. Some systems link duration to
                marriage length, others allow indefinite support in long-term
                marriages. This calculator uses a simple tiered rule of thumb:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Marriage &lt; 3 years:</strong> 0–1 year of alimony
                  (often none) – we suggest <code>0.5 × years married</code>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>3–10 years:</strong> about
                  <code>0.6 × years married</code>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>10–20 years:</strong> about
                  <code>0.8 × years married</code>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>&gt; 20 years:</strong> up to the full marriage
                  length, capped at 20 years in this tool
                </li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code
                  >Suggested duration (years) = factor × years married, capped
                  at 20 years</code
                >
              </div>

              <h3>Tax treatment and net income</h3>
              <p>
                Historically, in the U.S. alimony was often
                <strong>tax-deductible</strong> for the payer and
                <strong>taxable</strong> for the recipient. For divorces
                finalized after December 31, 2018, federal law generally removed
                this treatment.
              </p>
              <p>The calculator lets you toggle between:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Not deductible / not taxable:</strong> alimony is paid
                  from after-tax income and not taxed to the recipient.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Deductible / taxable:</strong> alimony reduces the
                  payer’s taxable income and increases the recipient’s taxable
                  income.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Using your estimated effective tax rates, the tool shows
                approximate <strong>post-alimony net monthly income</strong> for
                each spouse. This helps you see how the same gross payment can
                feel very different under different tax rules.
              </p>

              <h2>What is alimony (spousal support)?</h2>
              <p>
                Alimony, also called <strong>spousal support</strong> or
                <strong>maintenance</strong>, is money that one spouse may be
                ordered to pay the other after separation or divorce. The goal
                is usually to:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  help the lower-earning spouse meet reasonable needs, and
                </li>
                <li>
                  partially equalize the standard of living for a transition
                  period.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                It is different from <strong>child support</strong>, which is
                meant to support children and often follows stricter formulas.
              </p>

              <h3>Common factors courts consider</h3>
              <p>
                While laws differ, many courts look at similar factors, such as:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Length of the marriage</li>
                <li>Each spouse’s income, assets, and earning capacity</li>
                <li>Age and health of both spouses</li>
                <li>Standard of living during the marriage</li>
                <li>
                  Contributions to the marriage (including unpaid work and
                  supporting the other’s career)
                </li>
                <li>Childcare responsibilities and special needs</li>
                <li>Existing child support or property division</li>
                <li>In some places, marital misconduct or fault</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations of any alimony calculator</h2>
              <p>
                No online calculator can capture every nuance of your situation.
                Some jurisdictions have detailed formulas; others rely heavily
                on judicial discretion. This tool:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  does <strong>not</strong> apply any specific state or national
                  statute,
                </li>
                <li>
                  does <strong>not</strong> account for property division,
                  debts, or health insurance, and
                </li>
                <li>
                  does <strong>not</strong> replace legal advice from a
                  qualified attorney.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use it as a way to understand how income differences and
                marriage length can influence support, then discuss your
                specific facts with a family-law professional.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Can I rely on this number in court?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Judges are not bound by this calculator. They must follow
                the law in your jurisdiction and consider the evidence in your
                case. Lawyers and mediators may use tools like this as a
                starting point for negotiation, but final outcomes can be
                higher, lower, or zero.
              </p>

              <h3>What if my spouse is underemployed or not working?</h3>
              <p>
                Some courts can “impute” income to a spouse who is voluntarily
                unemployed or underemployed, based on their skills, work
                history, and job market. You can experiment by entering a
                reasonable estimated income for that spouse, but only a court
                can decide whether to impute income and at what level.
              </p>

              <h3>How do child support and alimony interact?</h3>
              <p>
                In many places, child support is calculated first using a
                statutory formula. Alimony may then be considered after
                accounting for child support and each parent’s share of
                childcare costs. This calculator does not compute child support;
                it only adds a small adjustment for dependents to reflect
                increased need.
              </p>

              <h3>When does alimony end?</h3>
              <p>
                Orders and agreements usually specify an end date or event, such
                as:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>after a set number of years,</li>
                <li>when the recipient remarries or cohabits,</li>
                <li>when either party dies, or</li>
                <li>when the court modifies or terminates the order.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always read your specific order or agreement and ask a lawyer if
                you are unsure.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I talk to a lawyer or financial planner?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Alimony affects your long-term finances, taxes, and
                retirement planning. A family-law attorney can explain your
                rights and obligations, and a financial planner or tax
                professional can help you understand the impact on your budget
                and future goals.
              </p>
